      {
        "type": "text",
        "content": "The Hanifi Rohingya script, while a modern invention, is structurally modeled upon the Arabic script and exhibits a key characteristic of many cursive, abjad-derived writing systems: its letters change shape based on their position within a word. This means that a single Hanifi Rohingya consonant character can have up to four potential forms, though for many letters, the forms are reduced or look visually similar."
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "table": {
          "headers": [
            "Form",
            "Description",
            "Function"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "Isolated",
              "The standalone shape of the letter when it is not connected to any other letter (for example, when written alone or separated by a space).",
              "Used at the beginning or end of a word if the previous letter does not connect, or if the letter itself does not connect to the next one."
            ],
            [
              "Initial",
              "The shape the letter takes when it appears at the beginning of a word or after a non-connecting letter.",
              "Connects only to the following letter (to the left, since the script is written right-to-left)."
            ],
            [
              "Medial",
              "The shape the letter takes when it is in the middle of a word.",
              "Connects to both the preceding (right) and following (left) letters."
            ],
            [
              "Final",
              "The shape the letter takes when it appears at the end of a word, connecting to the letter immediately before it.",
              "Connects only to the preceding letter (to the right)."
            ]
